# Janajātiya Oral Traditions and the Animistic Roots of Sanātana Dharma: Evidence, Correlations, and Continuities

## Overture: Reading Oral India with Rock-Hard Evidence

Indian civilization speaks in two registers at once: a textual register
(śruti/smṛti, śāstra, itihāsa-purāṇa) and an oral-ritual register
carried by *janajātiya* communities---forest epics, clan songs, cults of
groves and stones. Older scholarship tended to oppose a
"Vedic-Sanskritic Aryan" layer to a "tribal-animist non-Aryan" layer,
but this dichotomy is increasingly undermined by hard data from
archaeology, geology, and epigraphy. When we read the oral alongside the
material, unexpected continuities emerge: for example, Vedic-style fire
altars in mature Harappan contexts, an orally remembered **Sarasvatī**
river that geology has traced as a "fossil" river, epic memories of
cities lost to the sea that marine archaeology has corroborated, and
"tribal" deities elevated into the Sanskritic pantheon without erasing
their indigenous
priesthoods[\[1\]](https://jagannathjinkd.weebly.com/about.html#:~:text=languages%2C%20and%20so%20remains%20to,19).
Each such case study in this paper pairs oral/literary tradition with a
scientific or archaeological anchor from the Indian subcontinent
(Confidence levels **A--D** as explained below).

**Confidence rubric:** We attach a grade **A--D** to each load-bearing
claim. **A** denotes a claim tied to primary material
evidence---excavations, stratigraphy, dated inscriptions or
peer-reviewed scientific data. **B** indicates multiple convergent
secondary sources or strong interdisciplinary agreement. **C** marks an
inference with partial support (one of several possible
interpretations). **D** is reserved for propositions resting on living
oral memory or later textual testimony alone, without direct material
confirmation. We explicitly label major claims with these confidence
grades. (Grades can be combined for a single topic: e.g. a site
identification might be A, while an associated legend is B or C.) In
general, claims not paired with material anchors are deliberately
"down-badged" in confidence.

Two framing principles guide this study (in the spirit of clarity seen
in Debroy's writing and evidence-discipline seen in J. Sai Deepak's
works). First is a **paired-evidence rule**: cultural claims are,
wherever possible, directly paired with a material or primary anchor
(inscriptions, stratified finds, scientific analyses). Unpaired claims
(solely literary or oral) are still discussed, but explicitly flagged
with lower confidence. Second, **"script ≠ language" and "civilization ≠
single canon"**: the so-called Vedic/Sanskritic stream and the
*janajātiya* (indigenous tribal) streams have long been co-flowing and
intermeshed. Absorption and reciprocity---not abrupt rupture---best
explain India's long religious
history[\[2\]](https://www.indiafacts.org.in/excavations-show-the-cultural-continuity-of-the-vedic-harappans/#:~:text=Moreover%2C%20the%20area%20known%20to,trace%20of%20Aryans%20penetrating%20India)[\[3\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicak%E1%B9%A3u#:~:text=He%20succeeded%20his%20father%20King,2).
Hemchandra Raychaudhuri and B. C. Law, among others, argued that many
ancient Indian institutions and dynasties cannot be understood without
accounting for tribal
contributions[\[4\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicak%E1%B9%A3u#:~:text=During%20the%20excavation%20of%20Hastinapur,shows%20that%20%2055)[\[5\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicak%E1%B9%A3u#:~:text=He%20succeeded%20his%20father%20King,2).
This paper takes that integrative approach.

> **"एकं सद् विप्रा बहुधा वदन्ति"** --- Ṛg-Veda 1.164.46.  
> "Truth is one; sages speak it variously." (Jamison and Brereton
> 1.164.46)

Methodologically, we start with **A-class anchors**---for instance, the
fire-altars of Kalibangan, the flood stratum at Hastināpura, the
Ghaggar--Hakra (*Sarasvatī*) palaeochannel, and Dvārakā's submerged
architecture. These are presented with material details and scientific
dating. We then test how oral and textual memories map onto those
anchors: e.g. Vedic ritual texts alongside the Harappan fire-altars; the
Mahābhārata's flood legend against Hastināpura's
stratigraphy[\[6\]](http://www.youngintach.org/heritage-alerts-mar14#:~:text=%E2%80%9CBut%20I%20wished%20best%20of,of%20polished%20grey%20ware%20settlement)[\[4\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicak%E1%B9%A3u#:~:text=During%20the%20excavation%20of%20Hastinapur,shows%20that%20%2055);
Vedic and Brāhmaṇa references to a disappearing Sarasvatī against the
mapped
palaeoriver[\[4\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicak%E1%B9%A3u#:~:text=During%20the%20excavation%20of%20Hastinapur,shows%20that%20%2055)[\[7\]](https://indiageomorph.org/uploads/pdf/river-sys.pdf#:~:text=,Thesis%2C%20Centre%20for%20the%20Study);
and the purāṇic account of Dvārakā's submergence against
marine-archaeological
finds[\[8\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=many%20folds%20during%20the%20medieval,last%20two%20decades%20in%20the)[\[9\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=town%20by%20reclaiming%2012%20yojana,words%20like%20pattana%20and%20Dronimukha).
Where archaeo-astronomy is invoked (for dating epic events via celestial
markers), we cite scholarly attempts alongside appropriate
cautions[\[10\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicak%E1%B9%A3u#:~:text=the%20King%20of%20Vatsa%20,8).
Where we argue "tribal-to-mainstream" absorption (for example,
Jagannātha of Puri emerging from a Sāvāra tribal cult), we cite the
seminal Jagannāth studies and note the living **Daitā**
(Sāvāra-descended) ritual rights within that temple
ecology[\[1\]](https://jagannathjinkd.weebly.com/about.html#:~:text=languages%2C%20and%20so%20remains%20to,19).
Throughout, the unit of analysis remains within India (including Indian
territories like the Andaman--Nicobar Islands but excluding Southeast
Asia). Case studies span the *Dandakāraṇya* forests of central India,
the Indo-Gangetic heartland, Odisha and the eastern coasts, the western
seaboard (Dwarka, etc.), the Himalayan fringes, and peninsular
groves---underscoring that the phenomena of interest are pan-Indian.

