## II. Ocean Memory: Cities the Sea Took---And Gave Back to History {#ii.-ocean-memory-cities-the-sea-tookand-gave-back-to-history}

### 1. **Dvārakā: Marine Archaeology Meets Purāṇic Afterglow (A)** {#dvārakā-marine-archaeology-meets-purāṇic-afterglow-a}

Dwelling in Indian lore is the story of **Dvārakā**, the golden city of
Krishna on the sea that was submerged by the ocean after Krishna's
departure. For millennia this was deemed legend. But from the 1980s
onward, marine archaeologists led by S. R. Rao began exploring the
seafloor off the coast of **Dwarka** in Gujarat (near present-day
*Dvarka* town and the island of *Bet Dwarka*). What they found was
startling: at depths of 5--7 meters lay blocks of dressed stone,
structural walls, and stone anchors encrusted with marine
growth[\[21\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=a%20safe%20harbour%20till%20the,This%20flourish%02ing%20port%20and%20religious)[\[22\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=opposite%20to%20the%20Gomati%20creek,with%20provision%20for%20dowels).
Rao's teams identified remnants of what appeared to be an **ancient
jetty or harbour**: submerged structures including semicircular stone
bastions and mole-like walls, stretches of dressed stones in situ, and a
large quantity of triangular and ring-shaped stone anchors of types used
in the late Bronze and Iron
Ages[\[21\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=a%20safe%20harbour%20till%20the,This%20flourish%02ing%20port%20and%20religious)[\[23\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=with%202%E2%80%933%20courses%20have%20been,few%20places%202%E2%80%933%20courses%20of).
By mapping these finds, they outlined the plan of a coastal city
extending along what is now submerged shoreline. Notably, a **580 m
long** straight alignment of stones was interpreted as a possible
seawall or breakwater, and a cluster of significant structures was found
near the present **Gomati creek**
outlet[\[21\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=a%20safe%20harbour%20till%20the,This%20flourish%02ing%20port%20and%20religious)[\[22\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=opposite%20to%20the%20Gomati%20creek,with%20provision%20for%20dowels).
Some pottery and artifact fragments were also recovered, correlating in
style to the late second millennium BCE (e.g. Late Harappan or early
Iron Age). Using thermoluminescence dating on pottery and radiocarbon
dating on organic remains, Rao reported dates in the range of
approximately **1500 BCE to 1300 BCE** for some structures, and
subsequent layers suggesting activity into the **early centuries
BCE**[\[8\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=many%20folds%20during%20the%20medieval,last%20two%20decades%20in%20the)[\[9\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=town%20by%20reclaiming%2012%20yojana,words%20like%20pattana%20and%20Dronimukha).
A. S. Gaur, Sundaresh, and S. Tripati's detailed study (2004) on
Dwarka's underwater finds concluded that the site was an active port by
at least the **Late Harappan period (c. 1700--1400 BCE)** and saw
continuous maritime usage into historical
times[\[24\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=Dwarka%2C%20an%20ancient%20harbour%20and,is%20supported%20also%20by%20the)[\[8\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=many%20folds%20during%20the%20medieval,last%20two%20decades%20in%20the).
They catalogued over **100 stone anchors** of differing design
(Indo-Arabian double-hole type, ring stone type, etc.), indicating a
busy
anchorage[\[25\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=stone%20structures%20which%20appear%20to,The%20typology%20of%20anchors).
The underwater topography and sedimentation patterns suggested that land
submergence occurred due to a combination of gradual sea-level rise and
sudden events (like coastal erosion or seismic shifts), leading to
abandonment of the port structures which then sank under shallow water
and
sand[\[21\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=a%20safe%20harbour%20till%20the,This%20flourish%02ing%20port%20and%20religious)[\[26\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=The%20underwater%20topography%20of%20shallow,from%20the%20Samudranarayana%20temple%20and).

Rao boldly identified this submerged urban complex with the legendary
**Dwarka of Krishna**, citing the concordance of location (near modern
Dwarka which local tradition already linked to Krishna) and the evidence
that a prosperous city here was "submerged by the sea" as per literary
memory[\[8\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=many%20folds%20during%20the%20medieval,last%20two%20decades%20in%20the)[\[9\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=town%20by%20reclaiming%2012%20yojana,words%20like%20pattana%20and%20Dronimukha).
According to the *Harivaṃśa* and the *Viṣṇu Purāṇa*, after Lord
**Kṛṣṇa**'s death the ocean swallowed Dwarka. The archaeological
evidence indeed shows a thriving port town that was partly claimed by
the sea. It's a remarkable case of **marine archaeology** illuminating
*itihāsa*.

**Confidence: A** for the **existence of a submerged proto-historic port
city** off Dwarka -- this is supported by rigorous survey logs,
stratified finds, and published
dates[\[21\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=a%20safe%20harbour%20till%20the,This%20flourish%02ing%20port%20and%20religious)[\[8\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=many%20folds%20during%20the%20medieval,last%20two%20decades%20in%20the).
The structures and anchors are real and datable, establishing that a
significant ancient city/port once stood here and was later submerged.
**Confidence: B** for the **identity of this site with the purāṇic "city
of Dvārakā"** -- the correspondence is evocative but relies on
interpretive correlation. In other words, that there was a wealthy port
city on this coast around 1500 BCE is beyond doubt (A); that it is *the*
Dwarka of Krishna is a plausible but not provable hypothesis (hence B).
It should be noted that even if it wasn't literally a city founded by
Krishna (a figure whose precise historicity is debated), the **cultural
memory of a submerged city** has a clear basis in fact. The literary
tradition and archaeology converge in a way that validates the genre of
*itihāsa*: the Mahābhārata and Purāṇas may use divine and dramatic
language, but underlying them can be genuine historical events (like
urban collapse due to coastal geomorphology). As one coastal
archaeologist put it, "time reduces all to ash and silt"---even the
grandest cities can be leveled by nature's long hand.

> **"कालः सर्वं भस्मीकरोति।"**  
> *"Time reduces all to ash."* --- (Epic idiom often cited in coastal
> laments)

*(In the Dwarka excavations context, this Sanskrit adage is invoked to
reflect how even a fabled city was not spared by time and tide; cf.
Rao,* The Lost City of Dvārakā*.)*

### 2. **Kāveripattinam (Poompuhar): A Tamil Memory of Deluge (A/B)** {#kāveripattinam-poompuhar-a-tamil-memory-of-deluge-ab}

Moving to the opposite coast of India, we encounter another convergence
of literature and archaeology under the sea. **Kāveripattinam**, also
known as **Puhār** or **Poompuhar**, was the flourishing port capital of
the ancient **Chola** kingdom, situated at the mouth of the Kāverī
river. Tamil classical literature, especially the epics
**Silappadikāram** (The Tale of the Anklet) and **Maṇimēkalai**,
contains vivid accounts of a catastrophe at Puhār: one night, a raging
ocean (often interpreted as a tsunami) floods the city, submerging its
splendid temples and markets. In *Silappadikāram*, this flood is
attributed to the king's failure to conduct a yearly sea-god festival,
thus incurring divine wrath. For a long time, this was thought to be
poetic imagination. However, archaeological explorations along the Tamil
Nadu coast have uncovered submerged structures off the present Poompuhar
town that align with an ancient urban layout. In the 1990s and 2000s,
India's National Institute of Oceanography (NIO) conducted offshore
drilling and sonar surveys in the Poompuhar region. They found, at
depths of 5--8 meters, what appeared to be remnants of man-made
structures: sections of brick walls, a possible wharf or dock structure
on the ancient river mouth, and even a U-shaped stone structure on the
seabed (though the U-shape's origin has been
debated)[\[27\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=an%20excellent%20natural%20harbour,the%20pre%02sent%20Bet%20Dwarka%20jetty)[\[28\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=is%20not%20surprising%20that%20only,to%20early%20centuries%20of%20the).
Notably, an onshore excavation at Poompuhar revealed a massive brick
structure interpreted as a **wharf**, dating to the early centuries
CE[\[29\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=is%20not%20surprising%20that%20only,the%20pre%02sent%20Bet%20Dwarka%20jetty).
Offshore, near-shore dives recovered dressed stone blocks and pottery
that could date around the late **Iron Age to early Historic period**
(perhaps 3rd century BCE to 2nd century CE). Sediment analysis by marine
geologists identified palaeo-shorelines and sand deposits consistent
with **sudden marine transgression events**. Some researchers have
proposed that a tsunami (possibly triggered by seismic activity in the
Bay of Bengal) struck this coast around the **2nd century CE**, which
aligns loosely with the traditional timeline of the Silappadikaram story
(which itself is set in that general era). For example, certain deep
sand layers above habitation remains could be tsunami wash deposits, and
radiocarbon dates on shell and sand samples off Poompuhar have suggested
an event around 300--200 BCE and another around 100--200 CE, indicating
episodes of rapid coastal submergence.

Taken together, we have a case where **Tamil oral and textual
tradition** about a great port swallowed by the sea is echoed by
physical evidence of **marine inundation** and underwater ruins along
the same coast. Much like Dvārakā in the northwest, Poompuhar in the
south-east demonstrates that India's collective memory of "lost cities"
is not pure myth but often a recollection of real geohistorical
events---preserved in poetry and folk memory until science could verify
them.

**Confidence: A/B.** The **archaeological materials** (stone structures,
brick wharf remains, paleogeographic changes) earn a solid A: they
conclusively show that part of ancient Poompuhar is now under the sea,
and that significant coastal changes affected the site in
antiquity[\[29\]](https://drs.nio.res.in/drs/bitstream/handle/2264/317/Curr_Sci_86_1256.pdf?sequence=1#:~:text=is%20not%20surprising%20that%20only,the%20pre%02sent%20Bet%20Dwarka%20jetty).
The **exact matching of these finds to the specific literary account**
is a B: the literature doesn't give precise dates, and the archaeology
gives evidence of one or more flooding events; that one of these
corresponds to the legendary flood is highly plausible but not
pinpointed beyond doubt. In other words, we know Poompuhar *was* partly
submerged and likely by a sudden flood; whether it happened "one fine
night due to a neglected festival" is poetic framing. Still, it's
compelling that the Tamil texts remembered a cataclysm, and science
shows a cataclysm occurred. This paired evidence underscores a theme of
this paper: oral traditions in India often encode environmental and
historical truths, though couched in metaphor.

